#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:9
msgid "Foreword"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:11
msgid ""
"This book contains all the competitive scenarios for Space Empires 4X, "
"Close Encounters, Replicators, and All Good Things. The base game and "
"both previous expansions are necessary to take advantage of all the "
"options found here. These rules assume that you are using the updated "
"player aid cards provided with All Good Things. Cross-references to "
"sections will be included in parentheses, e.g., (5.7). References to the "
"Master Rule Book and the Solo/Co-Op Scenario Book will be notated "
"accordingly, e.g. (MRB 5.5) or (SSB 8.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:17
msgid "Standard Rules For Competitive"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:19
msgid "SCENARIOS"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:25
msgid "Player At-Start Forces"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:27
msgid "Unless otherwise specified, in"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:28
msgid ""
"each scenario each player gets the following: • A fully developed 30 CP "
"Homeworld. When playing with the optional rules for Facilities (MRB "
"36.0), the 20 CP Homeworld counter is used instead."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:29
msgid ""
"• Three Colony Ships, one Miner, four Shipyards (SY), and three Scouts "
"(SC) at their Homeworld."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:30
msgid "• One Flagship (optional, MRB 23.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:36
msgid "Customizable"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:38
msgid "Give each rule a shot before you judge it. A"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:39
msgid ""
"lot of thought and play went into them. However, once familiar with the "
"game, feel free to play the game any way you want – this game is meant to"
" be customized. You won’t offend the designer!"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:45
msgid "Galaxy Setup"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:47
msgid "Unless otherwise specified, Home System"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:48
msgid ""
"markers of a player’s color are placed in hexes that represent their home"
" territory and Deep Space System markers (white) are placed in all other "
"hexes – even hexes that could possibly have been a Home System area if "
"there were more players. Excess System markers are set aside."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:54
msgid "Warp Points and Doomsday Machines"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:56
msgid "Warp Point"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:57
msgid ""
"and Doomsday Machine counters should not be removed from the game at "
"setup. However, unless you are playing with the appropriate optional rule"
" (MRB 28.2; MRB 29.0), they are considered “open space” and are removed "
"from the game when flipped. Feel free to do this with every counter "
"players agree not to use in their game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:63
msgid "2-Player Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:65
msgid "The victory condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:66
msgid ""
"for each scenario, unless stated otherwise, is to destroy your opponent’s"
" Homeworld. However, the winning side can often become obvious before "
"that, and it is suggested that you end the game at that point."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:72
msgid "Multiplayer Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:74
msgid "Victory in multiplayer"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:75
msgid ""
"games, unless stated otherwise, is to destroy one opponent’s Homeworld. "
"When any player destroys any other player’s Homeworld, they become the "
"victor."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:81
msgid "Multiplayer Short Game Victory Condition (Colony"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:83
msgid ""
"Points): In addition to the condition in 1.1.6 above: • A player wins by "
"scoring 3 Colony Points. A player gets a Colony Point by:"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:84
msgid ""
"- Destroying (not damaging) another player’s Colony. This includes new "
"Colonies, but not Colony Ships. Once gained, this Colony Point cannot be "
"lost. Capturing another player’s Colony using ground combat also counts "
"towards this requirement (MRB 21.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:85
msgid ""
"- By having a 5 CP Colony in Deep Space or an opponent’s Home System. "
"Unlike points earned by destroying Colonies, this Colony Point is not "
"permanent. A player has it only for so long as they have a 5 CP Colony in"
" those sections of the map."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:86
msgid ""
"- A captured Colony may count for up to two Colony Points. Capturing "
"another player’s Colony yields 1 point. If that Colony grows to 5 CP, and"
" it is outside of the player’s Home System, it would then count as an "
"additional point (like any other Colony outside the player’s Home "
"System). The point for capturing it can never be lost, but the point for "
"having a Colony at 5 CP could be. If a player recaptures a Colony that "
"previously belonged to them it does not yield a Colony Point for "
"destroying a colony, but may yield a colony point for growing to 5 CP if "
"outside the Home System."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:87
msgid ""
"• A player wins the instant they score their third Colony Point and the "
"game ends immediately, even if it is mid-turn."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:88
msgid ""
"• If multiple players score their third Colony Point in the same Economic"
" Phase, the win goes to the player with the most Colony Points. In the "
"event of a tie, after the purchases for the Economic Phase are completed,"
" the players add up the CP value of all combat-capable ships they have on"
" the board and the winner is the player whose fleet adds up to the most "
"CP. In the event of another tie, the tied players share the win."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:89
msgid ""
"• If playing with Variable Map setup (3.2, 4.2), Colony Points are only "
"scored for destroying Colonies – not for having them."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:95
msgid "Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:97
msgid "Players are"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:98
msgid ""
"eliminated when their Homeworld is destroyed. Remove all of their pieces "
"and Colonies. Yes, we realize that their civilization would not disappear"
" when this happens. This represents them ceasing to function as a "
"political entity. The mechanism to bring the individual planets into your"
" empire is represented by colonization. The winner is the last player "
"standing. A player that eliminates another player gets a bonus 30 CPs in "
"the next Economic Phase. If the player they conquered has technology that"
" they do not possess, they may choose one level of two separate "
"technologies from that player and mark them as researched on their own "
"sheet. Homeworlds that are re-colonized by other players act as normal "
"Colonies (they normally produce at most 5 CPs)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:104
msgid "“Sinister” Victory Condition"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:106
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:110
msgid "A player wins by"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:107
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:111
msgid ""
"eliminating the Homeworld of the player on their left. This creates two "
"fronts for each player (one offensive and one defensive) and reduces the "
"likelihood of two players ganging up to eliminate a third. The archaic "
"definition of sinister is “related to the left side/left-handed.” The "
"notion that left- handedness was a sign of sin/evil has led to the modern"
" usage of sinister to mean so."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:117
msgid "Simultaneous Play"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:119
msgid "To speed up play (so that you can"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:120
msgid ""
"play more games!), many parts of Space Empires were designed to be done "
"simultaneously. Much of the early turns can be done simultaneously. When "
"playing with experienced players, it is suggested (if there is no threat "
"of direct interaction) that all players conduct their turns at once and "
"only wait for people in order to keep everyone in the same Economic "
"Phase. It is recommended to switch to sequential turns at the latest when"
" only two rows of deep space remain unexplored between players."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:126
msgid "Quick Start Variant"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:128
msgid "Use this suggestion for quicker"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:129
msgid ""
"play. After setting up, flip all Home System markers and place a full-"
"strength Colony on all non-barren planets. In this scenario, the players "
"do not start with any Colony Ships."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:135
msgid "(Small) Handicap Rule"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:137
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:141
msgid "Use this rule to provide a"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:138
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:142
msgid ""
"small advantage to a less-experienced player by increasing their CP "
"income during the early game. During each Economic Phase, the income of "
"that player’s Colonies will increase by two steps. For example, a Colony "
"Ship is flipped to its Colony side and a “3 Colony” marker is placed on "
"top instead of a “1 Colony.”"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:148
msgid "Variable but Balanced Home Systems"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:150
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:159
msgid "In this"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:151
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:160
msgid ""
"variant, all players have the same markers in their Home Systems, but no "
"player is aware of which markers are in play."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:152
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:161
msgid ""
"• All players set aside the following markers from their Home Systems: "
"two non-barren Planets, two 5-Mineral counters, one Asteroid, and one "
"Nebula."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:153
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:162
msgid ""
"• Each player then also sets aside all 8 of the new Home System markers "
"(these are marked with a “v” on the front side): one Supernova, one Fold "
"in Space, two 10-Mineral counters, one Space Wreck, one Space Pirate, and"
" two 10 CP Planets (see below)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:154
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:163
msgid ""
"• All these counters are organized into stacks of one counter of each "
"type per player. This will create 14 stacks. EXAMPLE: In a 3-player game,"
" there will be 14 stacks of 3 counters each – one from each player: One "
"stack with one Asteroids from each player; two stacks with one 10-Mineral"
" counter from each player, etc."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:155
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:164
msgid ""
"• Players collectively choose 6 of the 14 stacks. These stacks should be "
"chosen randomly and blindly so all players are unaware of which markers "
"will be included in the game. Each player takes their 6 markers and "
"shuffles them back into their Home System markers before setting up their"
" Home System."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:156
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:165
msgid ""
"10 CP Planets will grow to 5 CP like any other Colony and will then grow "
"to 10 CP the following phase. At 5 CP, place a flipped Colony Ship on "
"top; remove it when the Colony reaches 10 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:171
msgid "Gameplay Advice"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:173
msgid ""
"The play time for this game is in the 1 to 4-hour range for a 2-player "
"game, depending on the scenario. For multiplayer games, the play time "
"will be at the higher end of that range. Since new players tend to take "
"longer the first couple of times they play any game, here are some "
"suggestions to keep play time down in the early games."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:174
msgid ""
"• Start with just the basic rules. While they are fairly simple, the game"
" offers a lot of choices and decisions. Starting with just the basic "
"rules simplifies some of the choices and makes the first few Economic "
"Phases easier to wrap your head around."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:175
msgid ""
"• Start with the Small 2-Player Scenario. This is a scenario that "
"experienced players can finish in less than an hour and a half. Even if "
"it takes a new player an hour longer than that, it is easily manageable."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:176
msgid ""
"• For the first multiplayer game, play teams. It will drastically shorten"
" the playing time as you are learning the game. Try to pair an "
"experienced player with a beginner if possible."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:177
msgid "• Be aggressive! This is a game that rewards aggressive play."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:183
msgid "Player Alliances"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:185
msgid ""
"Some 3-Player or 4-Player scenarios include rules called UNEASY ALLIANCE "
"or BLOOD BROTHERS. When using either of these rules in any scenario, "
"teammates win or lose the game together. Also, you may not capture "
"Colonies from your allies with Ground Units (MRB 21.0) nor may you use "
"Boarding Ships (MRB 19.0) on your allies. You may never bombard Colonies "
"that your allies originally colonized."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:191
msgid "Uneasy Alliance"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:193
msgid "Teammates may never stack units"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:194
msgid "of any kind in the same hex and may not use each other’s MS Pipelines."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:200
msgid "Blood Brothers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:202
msgid "Teammates execute their turns at the"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:203
msgid ""
"same time, may stack together, may attack together, and may use each "
"other’s MS Pipelines for movement. However, they may not share research "
"or CPs."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:209
msgid "Definitions For All Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:211
msgid ""
"• Homeworld setup: Unless otherwise noted in the scenario rules, "
"Homeworlds may be placed in a player’s Home System hex marked with a red "
"“H” or a red-dashed line."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:212
msgid "• Hexes outside of the playing area are NOT playable."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:218
msgid "2-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:225
msgid "2-Player Small"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:227
msgid ""
"• This game is good for introducing players to the system. It is also "
"good for experienced players when they have a time constraint."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:228
msgid ""
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are NOT playable"
" (see exception below)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:229
msgid ""
"• There are 17 Deep Space markers. • There are 26 Home System markers on "
"each side. This means that Player 2 must choose one of the half-hexes on "
"the right edge of their playing area within their Home System. This half-"
"hex gets one of the System markers and is fully playable during the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:235
msgid "2-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:237
msgid ""
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are NOT playable"
" (see exception below). • There are 34 Deep Space markers. • There are 26"
" Home System markers on each side. This means that"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:238
msgid ""
"Player 1 must choose one of the half-hexes on the right edge of their "
"playing area within their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the "
"System markers and is fully playable during the game. • It is recommended"
" that you use Non-Player Aliens (MRB 18.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:244
msgid "2-Player Large"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:246
msgid ""
"• Half-sized hexes on the right side of the playing area are NOT playable"
" (see exception below). • There are 51 Deep Space markers. • There are 26"
" Home System markers on each side. This means that Player 2 must choose "
"one of the half-hexes on the right edge of their playing area within "
"their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the System markers and is "
"fully playable during the game. • Yeah, you might want to research "
"Exploration technology…"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:252
msgid "2-Player Extra Large"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:254
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 4-Player game. • There are 98 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:260
msgid "2-Player “3D”"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:262
msgid ""
"The title of this scenario promises more than it gives, but you’ll see "
"what we mean. • Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one "
"of the regions normally used in a 4-Player game. • There are 46 Deep "
"Space markers. • The two unused home regions get no System markers – they"
" are not in play. • More than not being in play, the unused home regions "
"need to be thought of as not being there. A player may move a ship into "
"an unused home region and come out in any other hex adjacent to that "
"unused home region. In essence, it is as if all the hexes adjacent to an "
"unused home region are adjacent to each other. • This is an attempt to "
"introduce a 3D element to the game board. Yes, it’s crude. Yes, it’s "
"simple. But we think it’s clever. ☺"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:268
msgid "2-Player Massive"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:270
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers as suggested by the "
"diagram. There are no guides on the game board to indicate this set up. •"
" Player 1 will have one Home System marker and Player 2 will have six "
"Home System markers that do not fit within the area indicated by the "
"line. These should be placed in any hex adjacent to that area. • There "
"are 98 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:276
msgid "“I Dare You To Play This”"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:278
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers as suggested by the "
"diagram. There are no guides on the game board to indicate this set up. •"
" The first two rows closest to each player will be filled by 25 of their "
"Home System markers. The remaining marker should be placed in any hex "
"adjacent to that area. • There are 98 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:284
msgid "2-Player Double Trouble"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:286
msgid ""
"• Each player uses all the pieces of their color, plus the Home System "
"markers of another color. One non-Barren planet and the Homeworld is "
"removed from each player’s additional color. • The Home System markers of"
" both colors are mixed together, and each player sets up these 50 Home "
"System markers as suggested by the diagram. There are no guides on the "
"game board to indicate this set up. • The first four rows closest to each"
" player will be filled by their 50 Home System markers. • There are 50 "
"Deep Space markers. • Each player can use the Colony counters of either "
"of their colors."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:292
msgid "2-Player Knife Fight"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:294
msgid ""
"• Setup: All 26 Home System markers are used for both players. However, "
"no Deep Space markers are used. One player sets up their Home System "
"markers in one of the four quadrants used in the 4-Player game (4.0). The"
" other player sets up their markers in quadrant fashion, but adjacent to "
"the first player’s quadrant with no Deep Space markers between them. Each"
" player places their Homeworlds in a hex marked with an “H” in the "
"diagram above. • Starting Ships: Both players start with four SCs and "
"four Colony Ships instead of three of each. Other starting units remain "
"as per 1.1.1. • Starting Tech: Both players start the game with Ship Size"
" 2, Ship Size 3, and Move 2 already researched."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:300
msgid "2-Player Galactic Capitol"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:302
msgid ""
"• A 2-player game with five rows of Deep Space in between and the "
"Galactic Capitol in the center hex labeled “GC” (MRB 28.1) • Including "
"the Galactic Capitol there are a total of 43 Deep Space markers. • There "
"are 26 Home System markers on each side. This means that both players "
"must choose one of the half-hexes on the right edge of their playing area"
" within their Home System. This half-hex gets one of the System markers "
"and is fully playable during the game. • This map can also be played "
"without the Galactic Capitol."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:308
msgid "2-Player – Single Talon Map"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:310
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of the map board from the game Talon, "
"also available through GMT Games. Two Empires set up on the opposite "
"sides of the board as shown. • There are 118 Deep Space markers. • "
"Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:316
msgid "2-Player – Both Talon Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:318
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of both map boards from the game Talon, "
"also available through GMT Games. The two boards are placed as above, "
"with two Empires set up on the opposite sides of the map as shown. Each "
"player’s Homeworld is placed in a hex marked with an “H”. Since there are"
" 30 Home System hexes, each player will have to use 4 of the new Home "
"System markers (marked with a “v” on the front side) at random. • There "
"are 198 Deep Space markers. • Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:324
msgid "2-Player – “The Belt” (Talon Map)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:331
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:368
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:641
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:797
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1034
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1102
msgid "Setup"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:333
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of the map board from the game Talon, "
"also available separately through GMT Games. Two Empires set up on the "
"opposite sides of the board as shown. Each player’s Homeworld is placed "
"in a hex marked with an “H.” The Home System markers from a different "
"Empire are placed in the red belt between the two Empires. Remove the "
"Homeworld, one non-Barren Planet, one Asteroid counter, and one Nebula "
"before mixing them. • There are 96 Deep Space markers"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:339
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:377
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:679
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:805
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1185
msgid "Special Rules"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:341
msgid ""
"• Partial hexes are not used. • Do not play with the Amazing Diplomats "
"Empire Advantage. • Non-Player Aliens are on all Deep Space and Belt "
"planets, including those that are not Barren. It is possible that you "
"will run out of NPAs in this scenario. If that happens, use a spare "
"counter to mark which planets still have NPAs and how many and draw "
"specific ships when they are attacked."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:342
msgid ""
"• All planets in Deep Space and the Belt give an Alien Technology Card "
"when colonized (MRB 11.0). If you run out of Alien Technology Cards, "
"reshuffle the discards to form a new draw pile. • It is recommended that "
"Doomsday Machines (MRB 29.0) and Warp Points (MRB 28.2) are NOT used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:348
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:1130
msgid "Victory Conditions"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:350
msgid "In addition to the normal victory"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:351
msgid ""
"conditions, a player can also win by having a Colony on six of the belt "
"planets."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:352
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:355
msgid ""
"Design Note: This is a longer game, not only because of the size of the "
"map, but because any new Colonies in the belt will be vulnerable. It will"
" be harder for one side to take a dominating lead and both sides should "
"end up deeper in the tech tree."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:361
msgid "2-Player – “Belt And Void” (Talon Map)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:370
msgid "Everything is the same as The Belt scenario, except"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:371
msgid ""
"that the Deep Space hexes are referred to as the “Void.” Add Deep Space "
"markers to every hex of the Void."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:379
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:382
msgid ""
"• In the Void, (but not the Belt hexes), there are strange radiation and "
"spatial properties that make it difficult for certain ships to enter. • "
"Only Decoys, Minesweepers, Scouts, Destroyers, Raiders, Miners, "
"Transports, Titans, and any advanced versions of those ships may enter "
"the Void. • Fighters and Ground Units that are carried by one of the "
"above vessels (or on a Colony) are also allowed. • Space Pirates are "
"allowed but captured Non-Player Alien ships are not allowed to move in "
"the Void. • Bases and Shipyards can be built at Colonies in the Void and "
"can move in the Void if using the On the Move Empire Advantage. • It is "
"not recommended that this scenario be played with Replicators. Design "
"Note: Taking a planet and establishing SYs in the belt to build bigger "
"ships is the key to the game. Ground Units will need to be used since "
"Colony Ships cannot enter the Void."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:388
msgid "3-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:395
msgid "3-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:397
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 3-Player game (denoted by the shading on the game "
"board). • The rest of the map (including the two hexes “behind” Player 2 "
"and Player 3) gets Deep Space markers. This will use 72 of them. • If all"
" players agree, players may place their Homeworlds in any hex of their "
"Home System. Otherwise, they use the hex marked with an “H”."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:403
msgid "3-Player Variable"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:405
msgid ""
"• Each player takes their Homeworld and places it randomly. A 20-sided "
"die can be used for this. If one is not available, then pieces of paper "
"numbered 1 to 13 can be drawn out of a cup. The first number rolled/drawn"
" is the row in which your Homeworld will be placed and the second number "
"rolled/ drawn is the number of hexes counted over in that row. If a "
"number is rolled that is out of range, then the die is re-rolled until "
"one in range is achieved. • All other System markers, both Home System "
"and Deep Space, are mixed together and randomly placed all over the map. "
"• This will often lead to unbalanced map layouts. However, for those that"
" love diplomacy, this is all part of the challenge. Those that have "
"weaker positions often gang up on the strong."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:411
msgid "3-Player Teams – 2 Vs 1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:413
msgid ""
"• Setup is the same as the 3-Player Standard scenario (3.1). • Mutually "
"agree or determine randomly which two players will be on the same team "
"versus the third player. • The two teammates operate under an UNEASY "
"ALLIANCE (1.3.1). • A player is eliminated when their Homeworld is "
"destroyed. The team wins as soon as they destroy the Homeworld of the "
"single player. The single player must eliminate both of the other players"
" in order to win. However, the single player does not get the 30 CP "
"conquering bonus listed in the Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition "
"(1.1.8). • Each of the allied players collect income normally, but all of"
" their ships and technology cost 1.5 times normal (after applying any "
"modifiers from e.g. Alien Technology Cards (MRB 11.0), round up). For "
"example, a Scout would cost 9 instead of 6, a Destroyer would cost 14 "
"instead of 9, and Tactics 1 Technology would cost 23 instead of 15. • "
"Maintenance and turn order bid would still be normal cost."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:419
msgid "3-Player Teams – 2 Vs 1 With Empire"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:421
msgid ""
"ADVANTAGES The setup and rules for this scenario are the same as given in"
" the 3-Player Teams – 2 vs 1 scenario (3.3), with the following "
"exceptions: • The team of two players pays the normal cost in CP for "
"everything. They do not have to pay 1.5 times the normal amount. • The "
"team of two players does not get any Empire Advantages (MRB 10.0), but "
"the single player draws six Empire Advantages and gets to choose four of "
"them. As normal, these Empire Advantages remain secret until used in such"
" a way that they would be revealed or a Colony is invaded."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:427
msgid "3-Player Teams - 2 Vs 1 With"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:429
msgid ""
"REPLICATORS • Setup is the same as the 3-Player Teams - 2 vs 1 scenario "
"(3.3). • Mutually agree or determine trandomly which two players will be "
"on the same team versus the third player. • The two teammates operate "
"under an UNEASY ALLIANCE (1.3.1). • In this game the Replicator’s "
"Colonies start at 1 CP instead of Start. They can still be bombarded back"
" down to Start and will then grow to 1 CP – 3 CP – Full. • A player is "
"eliminated when their Homeworld is destroyed. The team wins as soon as "
"they destroy the Replicator player’s Homeworld. The Replicator player "
"must eliminate both of the other players in order to win. However, the "
"Replicator player does not get the 30 CP conquering bonus listed in the "
"Multiplayer Long Game Victory Condition (1.1.8.)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:435
msgid "4-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:442
msgid "4-Player Standard"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:444
msgid ""
"• Each player sets up their 26 Home System markers in one of the regions "
"normally used in a 4-Player game (denoted by the outlined sections on the"
" game board). • The rest of the map gets Deep Space markers. This will "
"use 46 of them."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:450
msgid "4-Player Variable"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:452
msgid "• Setup is the same as the Variable 3-Player Map (3.2)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:458
msgid "4-Player Team Play"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:460
msgid ""
"• Setup is the same as the Standard 4-Player Map (4.1). • Mutually agree "
"or determine randomly what the teams will be. • Teammates can be "
"diagonally across from each other or next to one another depending on "
"personal preference. • Players must decide to play as an UNEASY ALLIANCE "
"or as BLOOD BROTHERS (1.3)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:466
msgid "4-Player Teams With Empire"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:468
msgid ""
"ADVANTAGES • Setup is the same as 4-Player Team Play (4.3). • All players"
" draw Empire Advantages as per either normal method (MRB 10.0)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:474
msgid "4-Player Teams – 3 Vs 1"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:476
msgid ""
"The setup and rules for this scenario are the same as given in the "
"4-Player Team Play scenario (4.3), with the following exceptions: • "
"Instead of 2 vs 2, this scenario is 3 vs 1. • The three players that are "
"on the same team are operating as BLOOD BROTHERS (1.3.2). • The player on"
" their own receives double the normal CP income from all Colonies except "
"their Homeworld. Example: If a player has a 30 CP Homeworld, two 3 CP "
"Colonies, one of which was"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:477
msgid "connected by an MS Pipeline, the player would get 43 CP."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:478
msgid ""
"• The single player draws three Empire Advantages (MRB 10.0) and picks "
"one. The three-player team draws a pool of five Empire Advantages and "
"each player will get to pick one of them. • Each of the players on the "
"three-player team starts with the technologies Terraforming 1 and "
"Scanners 1. • The single player must destroy all three of the enemy "
"Homeworlds."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:479
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:482
msgid "Design Note: This has the possibility of becoming a long scenario."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:488
msgid "4-Player Teams - 3 Vs 1 With"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:490
msgid ""
"REPLICATORS The setup and rules for this scenario are the same as given "
"in the 4-Player Teams – 3 vs 1 scenario (4.5), with the following "
"exceptions: • The Replicator player must be on the team with 3 players. •"
" The Replicator player draws two Empire Advantages (MRB 10.0) and keeps "
"one while the other two players on their team draw three Empire "
"Advantages total and each keep one."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:496
msgid "4-Player Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:498
msgid ""
"• There are 14 Home System markers used by each player. • From their Home"
" System markers, each player selects their Homeworld, five planets, one "
"Barren Planet, and seven Mineral counters. • Each player places their "
"Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” and their remaining 13 Home System "
"markers are mixed and placed within the boundaries shown in the diagram."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:499
msgid "• There are 94 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:505
msgid "4-Player Three Row Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:507
msgid ""
"• There are 25 Home System markers used by each player. • From their Home"
" System markers, each player removes one 5-Mineral marker, then places "
"their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” in the diagram above. • The "
"remaining 24 Home System markers for each player are mixed and placed "
"within the boundaries shown in the diagram. • The row of hexes at the "
"bottom of the map do not get markers and are not used. • There are 38 "
"Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:513
msgid "4-Player Four Row Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:515
msgid ""
"• There are 25 Home System markers used by each player. • From their Home"
" System markers, each player removes one 5-Mineral marker, then places "
"their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” in the diagram above. • The "
"remaining 24 Home System markers for each player are"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:516
msgid ""
"mixed and placed within the boundaries on the map. • There are 50 Deep "
"Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:522
msgid "4-Player Two Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:524
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires two copies of Space Empires 4X and is played on "
"two boards. Twelve blank hex tiles are used to connect the two boards on "
"their long edges. If terrain is revealed during the game in one of the "
"blank hex tile spaces, the blank is removed and replaced with the "
"appropriate Terrain tile (MRB 6.10). • Each player places their Homeworld"
" in a hex marked with an “H”. Since there are 31 Home System hexes, each "
"player will have to use 5 of the new Home system markers (marked with a "
"“v” on the front side) at random. • There are 188 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:530
msgid "4-Player Two Maps – Corners"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:532
msgid ""
"• Setup is a slightly modified version of the 4-Player Two Maps scenario "
"(4.10) - only add 4 new Home system markers instead of 5."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:538
msgid "4-Player Large (Talon Map)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:540
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of the map board from the game Talon, "
"also available separately through GMT Games. Each player’s Homeworld is "
"placed in a hex marked with an “H.” The remaining 25 Home System markers "
"for each player are mixed and placed within the boundaries shown in the "
"diagram above. • The rest of the hexes get Deep Space markers. This will "
"use 66 of them. • Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:546
msgid "4-Player – Both Talon Maps (Long Edge)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:548
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of both map boards from the game Talon, "
"also available separately through GMT Games. The two boards are arranged "
"as above. Each player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” "
"then the remaining 25 Home System markers for each player are mixed and "
"placed within the boundaries shown in the diagram above. • There are 154 "
"Deep Space markers. • Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:554
msgid "4-Player – Both Talon Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:556
msgid "(SHORT EDGE)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:557
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:565
msgid ""
"• Setup is a slightly modified version of the 4-Player – Both Talon Maps "
"(Long Edge) scenario (4.13)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:563
msgid "4-Player – Both Talon Maps (With Gaps)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:571
msgid "5-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:578
msgid "5-Player Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:580
msgid ""
"• There are 11 Home System markers used by each player. From their Home "
"System markers, each player selects their Homeworld, five planets, and "
"five Mineral counters. • A Replicator player uses their Homeworld, four "
"planets, one Barren planet, four 10-Mineral counters and one 5-Mineral "
"counter. • Each player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H”"
" then the remaining ten System markers are mixed and placed within two "
"hexes of the Homeworld. Some players will have a Deep Space marker within"
" 2 hexes of their Homeworld, they may choose which hex this is. • There "
"are 95 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:586
msgid "5-Player Tight"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:588
msgid ""
"• This uses the same map as the 5-Player Deep Space scenario (5.1). • "
"There are 19 Home System markers used by each player. From their Home "
"System markers, each player selects their Homeworld, eight planets, one "
"Asteroid, one Nebula, and eight Mineral counters. • A Replicator player "
"uses their Homeworld, seven planets, one Barren planet, two Asteroids, "
"two Nebulae, four 10-Mineral counters, and two 5-Mineral counters. • Each"
" player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” then the "
"remaining 18 System markers are mixed and placed within three hexes of "
"the Homeworld. • There are 55 Deep Space markers. When setting up this "
"map, at least one hex of Deep Space must be between each player’s Home "
"System hexes. • There may be a turn or two where you will need to use "
"spare numeral markers to keep track of the Colony growth for all five "
"players."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:594
msgid "5-Player - 3 Vs 2"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:596
msgid ""
"• Use the same map and setup as the 5-Player Tight scenario (5.2). • The "
"Replicator Player must be part of the 3-player side. • The 3-Player side "
"draws no Empire Advantages (MRB 10.0). • The 2-Player team draws six "
"Empire Advantages and decides together which four they will use. Each "
"player gets the benefit of only two of the cards. • Both teams operate as"
" an UNEASY ALLIANCE (1.3.1)."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:602
msgid "6-Player Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:609
msgid "6-Player Two Row Deep Space"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:611
msgid ""
"• There are 21 Home System markers used by each player, except player 5, "
"which only uses 20 Home System markers. • From their Home System markers,"
" each player removes two 5-Minerals, one non-barren planet, one Asteroid,"
" and one Nebula. Player 5 removes two Asteroids instead of one. • Each "
"player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” then the "
"remaining 20 Home System markers (19 for player 5) for each player are "
"mixed and placed within the boundaries shown in the diagram above. • "
"There are 25 Deep Space markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:617
msgid "6-Player Two Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:619
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires two copies of Space Empires 4X and is played on "
"two boards. Twelve blank hex tiles are used to connect the two boards on "
"their long edges. If terrain is revealed during the game in one of the "
"blank hex tile spaces, the blank is removed and replaced with the "
"appropriate Terrain tile (MRB 6.10). • Twelve blank hex tiles are used to"
" connect the two boards on their long edges. If terrain is revealed "
"during the game in one of the blank hex tile spaces, the blank is removed"
" and replaced with the appropriate Terrain tile (MRB 6.10). • Each player"
" places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” then the remaining "
"Home System markers for each player are mixed and placed within the "
"boundaries shown in the diagram above. • There are 156 Deep Space "
"markers."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:625
msgid "6-Player – Both Talon Maps"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:627
msgid ""
"• This scenario requires the use of both map boards from the game Talon, "
"also separately available through GMT Games. The two boards are arranged "
"as above, with each player’s Homeworld placed in a hex marked with an "
"“H.” The remaining 25 Home System markers for each player are mixed and "
"placed within the boundaries shown in the diagram above. • There are 102 "
"Deep Space markers. • Partial hexes are not used."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:633
msgid "Quick Conquest Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:635
msgid ""
"Although the Multiplayer Short Game Victory Condition (using Colony "
"Points, 1.1.7) has been popular for providing a shorter, non-team "
"multiplayer game, the point of this game has always been conquest. These "
"scenarios are meant to provide a quicker multiplayer game with conquest "
"as the victory condition."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:643
msgid ""
"• Each player places their Homeworld in a hex marked with an “H” in the "
"diagrams below. • No Mines or Minesweepers may be researched or used. • "
"Use the 30 CP Homeworld counters. • Use the Technology Head Start "
"Scenario Card (see the Card Manifest) in addition to any other Scenario "
"Cards. • The first player to destroy a Homeworld is the winner. • These "
"scenarios can also be played with teams."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:649
msgid "3-Player Quick Conquest (Refer To 3.1)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:656
msgid "4-Player Quick Conquest (Refer To 4.1)"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:663
msgid "Epic Scenarios for 2-8 Players"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:665
msgid ""
"• These scenarios require two copies of the game and are played on two "
"boards (see 4.10 for how to lay out two boards). • These are meant to "
"enable a game with more than four players, but any of the scenario setups"
" can be used for an epic scenario. The possibilities are numerous. - If "
"six players are in the game, using the 3-Player Standard setup on both "
"boards makes sense. - With seven players, using the 3-Player Standard "
"setup on one board and the 4-Player Standard setup on the other would "
"work. - A 2-Player game can be played where each player controls an "
"empire on both maps. - A 4-Player game could be played with two players "
"on each map using the “I Dare You to Play This” setup. In this case, it "
"is recommended that each player use all the Colony Ships of their own "
"color from both games. - An 8-Player game could be played with a Variable"
" Map setup (3.2 or 4.2). • If more than four players are playing, then "
"some of the same color playing pieces would have to be used. For example,"
" there might be two green empires. Empires of the same color should be "
"differentiated by starting the game on separate maps. When a unit crosses"
" over maps, it should be marked with a spare token of some sort, e.g., a "
"counter from some other game. • In an epic scenario, when one player "
"conquers another, they add all the conquered player’s pieces to their "
"build pool. • Warp Points: Warp Points (MRB 28.2) are the connection "
"between the boards. All six Warp Point 1s (three on each board) are "
"considered connected. The same with all six Warp Point 2s. Players should"
" agree on the number of Warp Points used on each map (i.e. whether they "
"want to discard the third warp point of each number as usual or keep them"
" in play). Deep Space markers should be mixed so that the same number of "
"Warp Points of the same ID (1 or 2) are on each map."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:671
msgid "Planetary Gate Scenarios"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:673
msgid "Planetary Gate scenarios are for those who can’t get enough ground combat."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:686
msgid "Planetary Gates"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:688
msgid "Each planet is"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:689
msgid ""
"connected to any other planet within three hexes by means of a Planetary "
"Gate. Ground Units (MRB 21.0) on one planet may move to any other planet "
"within three hexes via this Planetary Gate. That is considered their "
"entire move that turn. The Air Support Alien Technology card does not "
"enable Transports to use Planetary Gates. Colonies built on asteroids by "
"the Industrious Race are not connected by Planetary Gates."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:695
msgid "Barren Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:697
msgid "Barren Planets may be pre-placed in"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:698
msgid ""
"Deep Space between Home Systems so that it increases the likelihood that "
"players are connected by Planetary Gates. In the diagrams below, Barren "
"planets are placed on the hexes marked with a “B.” These are suggestions "
"for the 2-Player, 3-Player, and 4-Player game. However, players should "
"feel free to play without pre-placement of planets or come up with some "
"other mutually agreed upon layout. Players may also decide to remove all "
"Barren Planets from the remaining Deep Space System markers to limit "
"extra connectivity."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:704
msgid "Combat through Gates"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:706
msgid "If Ground Units are moved by a"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:707
msgid ""
"Planetary Gate and the destination planet is colonized by another player "
"or Non-Player Aliens (MRB 18.0), ground combat occurs normally. "
"Regardless of the ground combat technology of the invading player, "
"attacking units do not get to attack in the first round. The invasion and"
" the result are handled the same as if the planet was invaded from space."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:713
msgid "Retreats"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:715
msgid "Ground Units may retreat through gates, but"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:716
msgid ""
"only to friendly planets within three hexes that are free of enemy units."
" They may retreat before bombardment or during ground combat when it is "
"their turn to fire, but not during the first round. Fighters may not "
"retreat via Planetary Gates."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:722
msgid "Alien Planets"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:724
msgid "An NPA planet may be captured by"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:725
msgid ""
"invading through a Planetary Gate. In that case, any alien ships still in"
" orbit are removed from the game."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:731
msgid "Gates and Fighters"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:733
msgid "Fighters (MRB 15.2) may move between"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:734
msgid "planets like Ground Units, but only between friendly Colonies."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:740
msgid "Colony Ships"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:742
msgid "When a Colony Ship is purchased, it may"
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:743
msgid ""
"be purchased as a non-spacefaring Colony Ship. It still costs the same, "
"but it can be placed, without the use of a Shipyard, on any Colony that "
"produced 5 CP in that Economic Phase. It should be placed ship-side-up on"
" top of the existing Colony. A non-spacefaring Colony Ship can never move"
" into space but may travel though gates like Ground Units. It must "
"colonize the first uncolonized planet that it moves to. The ship is left "
"on the uncolonized planet and is flipped in the Economic Phase just as it"
" would be if it was a normal Colony Ship."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:744
#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:747
msgid ""
"Similar to space combat, the CO may enter a hex with enemy units only "
"when accompanied by friendly ground units, may not retreat, and is "
"destroyed if the enemy wins the combat. Design Note:Just when you think "
"you don’t need ships anymore, that fleet shows up and starts wasting your"
" Colonies from space. Then when you let your guard down on the ground, an"
" invasion force shows up in your Home System and starts spreading from "
"planet to planet."
msgstr ""

#: app/data/competitive_scenario_book.py:753
